\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. P. bellardii} All., {\i Fl. Pedem. }{\b 2:} 207 (1785) ({\i P. patulum} auct., non Bieb.; incl.{\i  P. kitaibelianum} Sadler, {\i P. novoascanicum} Klokov). Annual. Stem 20-100 cm, erect, usually much-branched. Leaves 25-45 mm, linear-lanceolate to elliptic-oblong, caducous. Flowers solitary or in axillary clusters of 2-4, subsessile, forming lax spikes; lower bracts leaf-like, the upper scarious and shorter than the flowers. Perianth 3-5 mm, divided almost to the base; segments greenish, erect. Nut 3-5 mm, glossy, not exceeding the perianth. 2n = 20.{\i  Cultivated ground. C. & S. Europe, extending northwards to c. }49°{\i  N. in France and c.} 55°{\i  N. in S. Ural.} Al Au Bl Bu Co Cz Ga Gr Hs Hu It Ju Rm Rs(C, W, K, E) Sa Si Tu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 12. P. patulum} Bieb.,{\i  Fl. Taur.-Cauc. }{\b 1:} 304 (1808) ({\i P. gracilius} (Ledeb.) Klokov,{\i  P. bellardii} auct., non L.,{\i  P. bordzilowskii} Klokov,{\i  P. cretaceum }Komarov,{\i  P. kotovii} Klokov,{\i  P. spectabile} Lehm. ). Like {\b 11} but more slender; leaves smaller and narrower, the uppermost linear; inflorescence more compact, with flowers crowded towards the ends of the branches; nut (1·5-)2-3 mm, equalling or slightly exceeding the perianth.{\i  Dry and sandy habitats, and as a ruderal. E.C. & S.E. Europe}. Hu Rm Rs(C, W, K, E).
