\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. P. arenarium} Waldst. & Kit.,{\i  Pl. Rar. Hung.}{\b  1:} 69 (1801). Annual. Stems 20-50 cm, diffusely branched from the base, procumbent or ascending. Leaves linear-lanceolate, acute, usually caducous. Bracts small, inconspicuous. Perianth pink and white, conspicuous, with patent segments. Nut 2 mm.{\i  Mainly in cultivated ground, especially on sandy soils. S. & E. Europe, northwards to }53°{\i  N. in E. Russia.} Al Bu Cz Ga Gr Hu It Ju Rm Rs(C, W, K, E) Tu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  arenarium} (incl. {\i P. pseudoarenarium} Klokov,{\i  P. janatae} Klokov, {\i P. venantianum }G.C. Clementi): Flowers rather distant, solitary or in pairs on the main branches, clustered and forming short, condensed terminal spikes on the lateral branches. Nut glossy. 2n = 20. {\i S.E. & E.C. Europe}.
